rounds.response:
In the big-blind (out of position after the flop) with J♣4♣ facing a pre-flop pot-size raise.

Hand strength:
- J4 suited – speculative, not strong; it can make a flush, two-pair, or trips, but none yet.
- P1’s raise strength unknown; we’re out of position post-flop.

Position & leverage:
- P1 only needs to call 10 into 30; their range may still be wide.
- We could 3-bet bluff to pressure P1’s potential weak/medium hands, but we’re holding 990 behind and a 3-bet to ~60 would risk 6% without much fold-equity versus typical blind-vs-blind ranges (and we block clubs).

The most profitable, low-variance line given our 1,000-chip starting stack and 10-hand battle is to see a flop in position and realize our equity cheaply.

[Call]

rounds.response:
Current situation:
- Board: Q♦ 7♥ 2♥ K♣  
- We still hold only 4♣ J♣, a complete (and worsened) brick — no pair, no draw, only a jack-high.
- Bet to us: 40  
- Pot after our call would be 120, so we’d be risking 40 to win 120 → breakeven ≈ 33%.  
- Our real equity is essentially 0%. Villain’s flop c-bet into a dry rainbow flop that went check-check suggests they hit something or fire routinely. Even if we hit a spade-perfect river nine, we’re still jack-high nut air.  

Hence, equity, odds, and future playability all urge a fold.

[Fold]

Opponent has proved willing to c-bet and apply pressure (he took down the first pot with a 100-pot-size flop bet). If they’re habitually continuation-betting wide, they’ll have a ton of misses on average flops; if they’re playing extra tight, we should exercise caution.

Plan:
1. Flatting 20 gives us a chance realize our equity in position post-flop.

Strategy: avoid bloating the pot out of position and exploit later with pressure.
